		<dc:creator>James</dc:creator>
		
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.rightonblog.net/?p=1614</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I use Firefox at work, and Safari on my Mac at home&#8230; I use the best browser for the job depending on the operating system I am using at the time. Never in my wildest dreams would it have crossed my mind that a specific ethnic group would need their own web browser.
Well apparently the [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I use Firefox at work, and Safari on my Mac at home&#8230; I use the best browser for the job depending on the operating system I am using at the time. Never in my wildest dreams would it have crossed my mind that a specific ethnic group would need their own web browser.</p>
<p>Well apparently the folks behind &#8220;<a href="http://www.blackbirdhome.com/">Blackbird</a>&#8221; feel that there is apparently a void in web browsers designed around black people. Yes, you read that right&#8230; a web browser for blacks. It is apparently written to bring news and events relevant to the black community to the front of the stack. Some of their noted features include;</p>
<ul>
<li>Black Search</li>
<li>Black News Ticker</li>
<li>Black Bookmarks</li>
</ul>
<p>Hell, even the browser is black.</p>
<p>Is this really where we&#8217;re headed? Will the Native Americans adopt Firefox? Jolly British folk adopt Safari? Latinos inherit Camino? Give me a break!</p>
<p>If race based news is of the utmost importance to you, chances are you&#8217;re already adept at finding the news you are looking for, why bring race into browser selection? What&#8217;s next, purchasing a computer and specifying your race so they preload it with the correct, ethnically balanced software?</p>
]]></content:encoded>
